**Abstract:**
Brief working notes dated June 25, 1991, titled "The Medieval Controversy." The document argues that while the use of reason within faith had preexisted the second and third entries of Aristotle's works, it had been subordinated to faith and to a historical comprehension of faith. What changed radically was the emergence of an autonomous understanding of reason that rendered impossible the historical comprehension of faith, making the opposition between reason and faith irreconcilable because Aristotelian reason is all-encompassing and autonomous.

**AI Recommendation:** Brief but important note capturing the central thesis about Aristotelian reason's impact on historical faith comprehension.

